  "doc_id": "35107",
  "text": "The most interesting discovery is the different sensitivity of spindle integrity to BAPTA and EGTA: rapid and complete microtubule depolymerization in the presence of DB-BAPTA but none at all in the presence of EGTA at equal or higher concentrations. This is despite EGTA having an affinity for calcium (123 nM at physiological pH; [CITATION_1] that is at least an order of magnitude greater than that of DB-BAPTA (K d = 1.6 μM) and despite the ability of EGTA to inhibit egg activation in all buffer compositions (Table 1) . This different sensitivity is reminiscent of that found in another calcium-mediated process: neurotransmitter release in the presynaptic nerve terminals of squid giant synapse [CITATION_2] . A large body of literature has yielded detailed mechanistic understanding of this system and the different responses to BAPTA and EGTA [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The close proximity, and indeed the direct molecular contact, of the calcium source (voltage-gated calcium channels) and calcium sensor (the vesicular protein synaptotagmin) EGTA, and UV-induced activation of caged calcium chelator diazo-2 [CITATION_5] . Our approach has the distinct advantage of revealing the direct effect of intracellular calcium buffering. Our data clearly indicate that BAPTA-based calcium chelators (DB-BAPTA and uncaged diazo-2), but not EGTA, caused rapid collapse of meiosis spindles. The effect of DB-BAPTA was clearly due to calcium buffering, as indicated by the inverse relationship between concentration of free calcium in the buffer and speed of spindle high and nonphysiological concentrations of calcium, 0.5 mM or higher, inhibit microtubule polymerization [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Physiological calcium concentrations (e.g., 1.2 μM at fertilization; [CITATION_8] clearly do not destabilize spindle microtubules or interfere with spindle function. As shown here, pricking (or water injection) caused immediate calcium elevation ( Figure 1B ), but metaphase II spindle remained stable and completed anaphase and polar body emission ( Figure 5A ). This is in contrast to BAPTAtype buffers (Figures 4, A and B, and 5B) or nocodazole [CITATION_9] , which caused immediate collapse of microtubule spindles and clustering of chromosomes.",
